{
  "text": "In addition to inhibiting HSV-1 replication in vitro, macrophage-derived NO has been shown to have anti-HSV properties in vivo. In a mouse model of HSV-1-mediated corneal disease, iNOS was highly induced in the trigeminal ganglion (TG) of HSV-1-infected mice, and its expression was markedly reduced in mice depleted of macrophages [CITATION_1] . Depletion of macrophages prior to HSV-1 infection resulted in markedly reduced iNOS expression and higher viral loads in the TG of infected mice [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , suggesting that macrophages were the main source of iNOS expression in the affected tissues following HSV-1 infection and that NO had important anti-HSV-1 properties in vivo. Consistent with these data, inhibition of NOS activity resulted in increased viral loads in the TG [CITATION_4] . Additional studies showed that F4/80 + GR-1 + inflammatory monocytes were recruited to the eye via an IFN-α-driven CCL2 gradient and restricted HSV-1 replication in that tissue via NO production [CITATION_5] . It was further shown that NO production by F4/80 + macrophages in the brains of HSV-1-infected mice blocked viral replication in a partially TLR2-and TLR9-dependent mechanism [CITATION_6] . Finally, following footpad inoculation, HSV-1-infected Nos2 −/− mice displayed a delayed clearance of virus from the dorsal root ganglia (DRG) and exhibited an increase in the frequency of virus reactivation in DRG [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "8823810",
